70. viciniae, partitive gen. depending on leuc, as osten aster ubi, quo, nusquam, etc. lmc visiniam is a needless correction, and huic viciniae, given by the MSS, a good instance osa copyist's blunder.

71. cognatorum neglegentia. This means a good deal in the mouth osan Athenian. At Athens, if an orphan girl was left poor, the next of kin was bound by Solon's law to marry her or to provide a sub- stantial dowry. Cf. Phor. 125. Cognatas is not used in the technical Roman sense, but as a translation of the Greek ἀγχιστεύς. The ἀγχιστεύς in this ease was Crito, who appears 796. As a citizen of Andros he was not subject to the Athenian law3 so there is no reason to suppose that it was his legal duty to provide sor Chrysis at Andros. He does not appear to have objected to inheriting anything that she might have lest at her death.

74. duriter, ‘with hard work) Adverbs in -ἱίεν, formed from adjectives in -us, are common in early Latin, e. g. avarz'ter, amiciter, mzmdz'tcr; later the termination -e became usual, but note humaniter (as well as humane) and naviter as exceptions.

81. esset, from csse, not from edere, as suggested by the older commentators.

82. egomet. This omission of a verb of ‘saying’ is common in Terence. Cf. 336. So Verg. Aen. 1. 37 haec serum, 3. 99 haec Phoebus.

83. habet. The regular exclamation over a gladiator who had received a blow. So lzoc habet Plaut. Most. 715, Verg. Aen. 12. 296.

84. venientis aut abeuntis, i. e. on errands to and from the houses of their respective masters.

88. quid, as in common talk we sometimes begin an explanation with ‘why.'
